                        <additions>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="a1">
                                    <desc type="Condemnation"/>
                                    <locus target="#51v"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>The note excommunicates whoever sells the book for starvation or poverty and whoever steals it.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a2">
                                    <desc type="OwnershipNote"/>
                                    <locus target="#51v"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en">This book belongs to Kǝsāda Qāl, whose wife is Birut Ḥāwit, whose father is ʾAfa Krǝstos, and whose mother is .... The scribe is Tābor.</q>
                                    <p>The note states that the book belongs to <persName corresp="PRS10769KesadaQ">Kǝsāda Qāl</persName>. His wife <persName corresp="PRS10770BirutH">Birut Ḥāwit</persName> and his father <persName corresp="PRS10771AfaKre">ʾAfa Krǝstos</persName> are also mentioned. The note also mentions <persName corresp="PRS10768Tabor">Tābor</persName> as the scribe</p> 
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a3">
                                    <desc type="ScribalNoteCompleting"/>
                                    <locus target="#137r"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez">ተፈጸመ፡ ዘዕዝራ፡ ፫ ወተጽሕፈት፡ ዛቲ፡ መጽሐፍ፡ ዕዝራ። ዘአጽሐፈኒ፡ ... ወጸሓፊሁ፡ መልከ፡ ጼዴቅ፡ ከመ፡ ይኩኖ፡ ለተዝካሩ፡ ወለተዝካረ፡ ደቂቁ፡ ወይዕቀቦ፡ እግዚአብሔር፡ እምኵሉ፡ እኩይ፡ ወያኑኅ፡ መዋዕሊሁ፡ በዲበ፡ ምድር፡ ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ አሜን፡ ወአሜን፡ ለይኩን፡ ለኩን።</q>
                                    <q xml:lang="en">Ezra 3 is finished, and this book of Ezra has been written. The one who commissioned me is ..., and its scribe is Malka Ṣedeq. Shall his memory and the memory of his sons be commemorated, and may God protect him from any evil and make his days long on the Earth, forever and ever, amen, amen. So be it, so be it.</q>
                                    <p>The note follows <ref target="ms_i4"/>. It mentions <persName corresp="PRS10772MalkaS">Malka Ṣedeq</persName> as the scribe. The Book of Ezra and Nehemiah is here labelled Ezra 3, according to the Ethiopian numbering.</p>
                                    <listBibl type="text">
                                        <bibl><ptr target="bm:Pereira1919Ezra"/><citedRange unit="page">648</citedRange></bibl>
                                    </listBibl>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a4">
                                    <desc type="CalendaricNote"/>
                                    <locus target="#142r"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez">ዘአርዓያ፡ ዘሳቤላ፡ ፱ፀሐይ፡ ወ፩ዘመን፡ ፯፻ወ፸ወ፰። ወታሰዓይሰ፡ ዘመን፡ ዓመታቲሁ። ፯፻ወ፸ወ፯። ዘሳቤላ፡ ቀመር፡ ፰፻ወ፯፻ወ፩ለ፩፡ ዘመን፡ ፰፻፡ ዓመት። ዝዕዝራ፡ ቀመር። ፵ወ፱ወ፩ቀመር፡ ፻ወ፵ወ፫ዓመት። ዘሄኖክ፡ ቀመር፡ ፲ለ፩ዘመን፡ ፯፻ዓመት። ለእግዚአቭሔር፡ ዕለታቲሁ፡ ፯ወበኀቤነሰ፡ ዕለታት። ፪፻፼ወ፭፼ወ፹፻።</q>
                                    <q xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>The note records the number of cycles and years per cycle according to the computation systems of Sibyl, Ezra and Enoch.</p>
                                    <listBibl type="text">
                                        <bibl><ptr target="bm:Schleifer1910Weisheit"/><citedRange unit="page">3a-3b</citedRange></bibl>
                                    </listBibl>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a5">
                                    <desc>List of canonical books</desc>
                                    <locus target="#142"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>The note lists the books of the Old and the New Testament according to the Ethiopian canon. The total number of books is also provided.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a6">
                                    <desc type="CalendaricNote"/>
                                    <locus target="#142"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en">The days since Adam until the end of the world (are) 2.556.750; one cycle (has) 194.180 days; (the number of) cycles of Adam (is) 13, each cycle (has) 532 years. The cycles of the Jubilees (are) 142 seven-year-cycles, each cycle (has) 42 years.</q>
                                    <p>The note records the number of days since Adam until the end of the world, the number of days and years per cycle according to the computation system of Adam.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a7">
                                    <desc type="ScribalNoteCompleting"/>
                                    <locus target="#142"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en">(The book of) Ezra (and) Sibyl is finished. Who allowed me to finish this book with my hands, the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit, shall be glorified now and ever, forever and ever. Amen. Who wrote it is me, Tābor, the sinner; remind of me.</q>
                                    <p>The note follows <ref target="ms_i5"/>. It mentions <persName corresp="PRS10768Tabor">Tābor</persName> as the scribe.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a8">
                                    <desc type="Poem"/>
                                    <locus target="#143"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>Rhymed poem in honor of <persName corresp="PRS6819Mary">Mary</persName>, incomplete</p>
                                    <p/>
                                </item>
